 head for those rare obscure specialty screws, but extremely useful at the right moment.<br><br>So why do so many of us dislike the current incarnation of the skill? I'd say there are two overall reasons, the first being the most important - its name.  It is called &quot;Act of Valor&quot;, implying a lot of things, especially to the more RP slanting paladin. Its current effect isn't Valorous, but when I look at people's suggestions for how to improve AoV ... they just don't work for a player skill.  Sure, killing myself to CH 6 people would be a wonderful valorous act, and I would love the ability - for the casual gamer or the light raider that could be a great thing to do on those rare occasions at just the right time.  But you have to look at what those abilities could be used to do - if you brought a bunch of paladins to a raid, all with AoV primed and ready to eat through xp, think of how much healing power you could have - with AoE heals, or group LoH's or CH's, or any of these other things, they all seem to have incredibly balance repercussions - to us /they/ might be worth a death, but to a die hard raider (from what I gather) that's a ton of gain for little cost.  I think that's why AoV is like it is now - its balanced for the uber hard core raid, the place where something like this could most be abused.  Again, not a commonly used tool, but just one for were it counts, something to add in to list of LoH, HWoP/WoH, DA, BMB/DS, /disc sanctification, etc.<br><br>I guess my point is this: that for the many of us that don't like AoV, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> it wasn't made for us</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br><br>And as to the original poster's AoV idea - I rather like it, but I don't like these &quot;percent chance on death things&quot; - I much prefer certainty.  Those cleric death pact spells never seem to work <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END